Based on the foregoing, we reiterated our recommendations that Management conduct more extensive tax campaign so that landowners are apprised of the advantages/services that the Municipality would render if taxes are paid;

Develop an efficient and effective monitoring and collection system so as to intensify the collection of its outstanding RPT/SET Receivables; and

Avail of all the possible remedies provided under the Rules and Regulations Implementing the Local Government Code of 1991 to enforce the collection of RPT.

However, we reiterated our recommendations that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Constantly issue demand letters to notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances. If settlement was not received, withhold from their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate;
Issue demand letters to employees who already resigned and transferred to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
Request the write-off of the unliquidated balance of cash advances of the dead employees;
Not grant additional cash advance to concerned officials and employees unless the previous cash advances granted to them have been liquidated; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of the above-mentioned laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that Management through the Municipal Accountant to:
Trace the history of the account;
After tracing, determine the extent of completion of the project/s;
Draw adjusting and/or correcting entries as necessary; and
Institute stricter review and monitoring controls over the payment of advances to contractors and the corresponding recoupment thereof in order to prevent unnecessary accounting oversights and, most importantly, avert loss of government funds.

The Municipal Accountant to record the procured supplies and materials as inventories upon purchase and the corresponding expense accounts must be taken up only upon issuance/s thereof;
The GSO to prepare and submit to the Municipal Accountant the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI), duly supported with the original copy of Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) on weekly or monthly basis. Thereafter, the Municipal Accountant should adjust the inventory account for whatever consumption on the basis of the submitted SSMI; and
The Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer maintain Supplies Ledger Cards (SLC) and Stock Cards, respectively, for each commodity/stock.

We recommended the following to Management:
The Municipal Accountant, General Services Officer and Municipal Engineer to work more closely and exert all efforts in locating documents and information pertaining to the road networks of the LGU for CY 2015 and prior years to properly recognize the same in the LGU’s Financial Statements for a fair presentation of the PPE account;
The Municipal Accountant to trace the expenditures for road networks in CYs 2016-2018 that were recorded in various PPE accounts and to reclassify thereof in the Road Networks account;
The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects already recognized in the books of the agency;
The General Services Officer maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and shall keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and
The Municipal Accountant prepare the Journal Voucher to record the inventory of the local road network and its components in the general ledger and the Local Road Network Ledger Card.  He shall keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network, and ensure that these are 100 percent booked-up in 2019 and thereafter consistent with COA Circular No. 2015-008. Full disclosure on road networks should be made in the Notes to the Financial Statements of the LGU.

