Direct the Municipal Health Officer to submit the approved DTRs, accomplishment reports, and office order/ work arrangements;
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all claims against government funds, specifically the SRA and AHDP, are supported with complete documentary requirements as provided under Section 4 (6) of Presidential Decree (PD) of 1445

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended that the:
Municipal Accountant record the disbursements of the projects charged against the Development Fund to appropriate accounts;
Municipal Engineer (i) being one of the members of the Inspectorate Team, ensure that the information contained in the Committee on Inspection Report are consistent with the information appearing in the payrolls and DTRs of the laborers; (ii) monitor the implementation of the Job Order prepared for each project, particularly, the daily rate of the laborer; (iii) provide explanation on his reimbursement amounting to P1,272.57 for the payment of electricity used during the implementation of the project – Improvement and Expansion of Cabolutan Barangay Multi-Purpose Hall; and (iv) properly plan the schedule of implementation of projects charged against the Fund taking into consideration the procurement timelines to be undertaken thereon;
Municipal Accountant and the Inspectorate Committee jointly coordinate in the determination on whether or not the procured materials are delivered within the date agreed upon in the PO and impose penalties upon the supplier, when applicable;
Municipal Treasurer effect the following fund transfers: (i) an amount of P1,226,420.00 from LBP Account No. 1162-1084-80 to LBP Account No. 1162-1018-26 for the disbursements erroneously charged against the latter account; and (ii) an amount of P27,000.00 from LBP Account No. 1162-1084-72 to LBP Account No. 1162-1084-80 for the payment of materials erroneously charged against the latter account.  To avoid recurrence of these cases, he should be careful and cautious in the evaluation of the disbursement vouchers submitted to him and in the issuance of checks thereof; and
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer carefully prepare the documents such as the List of Vouchers/Projects for 20 percent DF and the Report on PPAs by providing complete and accurate information for the benefit of the users thereof.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended that the:
MDRRMO (i) monitor the implementation of the projects classified as CO in the prior year/s.  If these were not completed as of year-end, include these projects in the LDRRMFIP of the following year.; and (ii) include all the equipment purchased in the current and prior years with complete details in the template – Inventory of Equipment Purchased Out of DRRMF/Donations as of December 31, 2021;
MDRRMO and the Municipal Accountant jointly coordinate in the classification of projects in the Plan to be able to record the corresponding disbursements to appropriate accounts;
Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant (i) effect the various fund transfers and the necessary adjusting entries mentioned in this report in order to arrive at the correct balances of the affected bank accounts as well as the correct balance of the Trust Liabilities - DRRMF account; and (ii) transfer the unexpended balance of 70 percent Mitigation Fund - MOOE for CY 2021 amounting to P416,407.10 to the Trust Fund;
Municipal Treasurer properly evaluate the disbursement vouchers submitted to him to be able to issue the checks from the appropriate bank accounts;
Municipal Engineer (i) monitor the implementation of the Job Order prepared for each project, particularly, the daily rate of the laborer; and (ii) properly plan the schedule of implementation of projects charged against the Fund taking into consideration the procurement timelines to be undertaken thereon;
Municipal Accountant (i) record the disbursements related to the same project in uniform accounts; and (ii) see to it that all the transactions affecting the Trust Liabilities - DRRMF and the Calamity Fund bank account were disclosed in the List of Vouchers, Notes to Financial Statements and the Report on Utilization of DRRMF.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended that the GFPS TWG:
communicate with the Local Finance Committee during the preparation of the budgets in order that the minimum budgetary requirement for GAD Fund provided in JMC No. 2013-01 is satisfied considering that the appropriations appearing in the GPB were based on the estimated Annual Budget of the LGU.  The appropriations, in case of issuance of Supplemental Budgets, were not considered.  Furthermore, he should be guided by the provisions of the aforementioned Circular on the provision of separate appropriations for GAD PPAs.  Those attributed programs identified in the GPB should be existing PPAs of the Municipality wherein portion or whole of the budgets may be attributed to GAD;
properly evaluate the supporting documents of the disbursements of GAD PPAs to be able to provide accurate and reliable information in the preparation of Project ARs and GAD AR;
monitor the disbursements charged on the GAD activities to avoid incurrence of excessive disbursements.  Also, the budgeting of GAD activities should be properly planned so as not to utilize the fund without appropriations;
see to it that the information contained in the related documents/reports such as Project Proposals, GPB, List of Vouchers, Project ARs and GAD AR were consistent;
prepare the Project ARs and GAD AR with full disclosure of the necessary information for the benefit of the users thereof; and
submit the lacking documents noted in the attachments of the GAD AR.
Moreover, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant evaluate the nature of the disbursements for appropriate recording.

